The <FILL_HERE> placeholder should be replaced with code to write the `output` string to a file named `filename` and then to upload that file to a Telegram chat using the Telegram Bot API. 

Here's an example of how you might complete the code:

```csharp
// Write to file
File.WriteAllText(filename, output);

// Upload to Telegram
string botToken = "YOUR_TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN";
string chatId = "YOUR_TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID";

using (var client = new HttpClient())
{
    using (var formData = new MultipartFormDataContent())
    {
        // Add file to form data
        var fileContent = new ByteArrayContent(File.ReadAllBytes(filename));
        fileContent.Headers.ContentDisposition = new ContentDispositionHeaderValue("form-data")
        {
            Name = "document",
            FileName = filename
        };
        formData.Add(fileContent);

        // Send POST request to Telegram API
        var response = await client.PostAsync($"https://api.telegram.org/bot{botToken}/sendDocument?chat_id={chatId}", formData);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
    }
}
```

Please replace `"YOUR_TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN"` and `"YOUR_TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID"` with your actual Telegram bot token and chat ID. 

Also, this code assumes that you have the `System.Net.Http` namespace included at the top of your file. If it's not, you can add it with:

```csharp
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Net.Http.Headers;
```

