This function uses `fgets` to read a line from the file. If `fgets` fails (i.e., it returns NULL), it frees the allocated memory and returns NULL. Otherwise, it returns the buffer. Note that this function allocates memory for the line it reads, so you should free the memory after you're done using the line.

Also, please be aware that this function doesn't handle newline characters. If the line read from the file ends with a newline character, `fgets` will include it in the string. If you want to remove the newline character, you can use the `strtok` function.

Lastly, the function doesn't check whether the allocated memory is large enough to hold the line. If a line is longer than 1024 characters, this function will overflow the buffer. You might want to increase the size of the buffer or check the length of the line before reading it.

